I think this may be Rose Sanderman rather than Sanderson (albeit the captioning on the image above is clearly &#8220;Sanderson&#8221;).

There is another LOC/Bain photograph available at the <a href="http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.pnp/ggbain.15305" rel="nofollow">LOC</a> that shows the same woman, and is identified as Rose Sanderman:

&#8220;Rose Sanderman (LOC)&#8221; by <i>Bain News Service</i>
<a href="http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.pnp/ggbain.15305" rel="nofollow"><img src="http://memory.loc.gov/service/pnp/ggbain/15300/15305t.gif" alt="Rose Sanderson (LOC)" alt="Rose Sanderson (LOC) by library_of_congress" /></a>

Additionally, there is a photo of this same woman, managed by <a href="http://www.corbisimages.com/Enlargement/Enlargement.aspx?id=VV15016&amp;caller=search" rel="nofollow">Corbis</a>, with the original caption of <i>&#8220;Auto Parade of the Suffragists on Fifth Avenue, May 1. New York, New York: Rose Sanderman, the bugler.&#8221;</i>

Of course, since the publishing of this wonderful photograph by the <i>Library of Congress</i>, references to the photo, and the name &#8220;Sanderson&#8221; have been picked up by scores of other sources, including <i><a href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Rose-Sanderson-Votes-for-Women.jpeg" rel="nofollow">Wikimedia</a></i>, so the quantity of references is not on the side of Sanderman ;-) &nbsp; To keep it interesting, Bettmann/Corbis also has a different photo of Rose playing her &#8220;bugle&#8221; in Washington, DC., and in <a href="http://www.corbisimages.com/Enlargement/Enlargement.aspx?id=BE040980&amp;caller=search" rel="nofollow">that photo</a> she is [mis]identified as <i>Sanderson</i>.

While there is little information about Rose &#8220;Sanderson&#8221;, <i>The New York Times</i> reported several stories on the fanciful activities of Rose Sanderman. In extensive coverage of National Women's Suffrage Day in New York City, May 2, 1914, <i><a href="http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9A07EFD81E39E633A25750C0A9639C946596D6CF" rel="nofollow">The New York Times</a></i> referred to Miss Rose Sanderman as the &#8220;official trumpeter for the celebration.&#8221;

An article headlined &#8220;<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9406E5D71F39E633A25755C1A9619C946596D6CF" rel="nofollow">GIRLS CAPTURE WALL ST.</a>&#8221; describes a big crowd at a suffrage rally on July 15, 1914. Commenting on the large crowd of men: &#8220;You see,&#8221; said Miss Rose Sanderman, &#8220;they thought that young girls didn't want the vote&mdash;that it was only the older women who wanted it. But when they saw us they realized their error...&#8221;


